== Research Experience

#set par(hanging-indent: 0pt, spacing: 0.8em)

All the research experiences I describe below stem from research opportunities
which I have pursued from my own initiative during my undergraduate studies
at the University of Toronto.

My most recent (ongoing) and pertinent research experience, which has directly spurred my
interest in this proposed project, is an independent research project that I
conducted under the supervision of Professor Jeffrey Steele.
After getting in contact with Professor Steele and proposing my idea, I began
formally working with him in September 2023.
I spent the next four months narrowing my research focus and methodology through
an extensive literature review process.
The independent project investigated individual differences in language aptitude
and working memory, and how these cognitive constructs predict gains in
phonetic production abilities for beginners learning French in a classroom setting.
With the help of Professor Steele, I designed a longitudinal study consisting of
seven tasks, four of which are production tasks that target four separate features
in speakers' oral proficiency.
The rest measured language aptitude, working memory, and language background.

In December 2023, I independently programmed the study website using
React and Next.js.
The website handles data collection for all of the oral production tasks,
the background questionnaire, and contains instructions for completing the other
tasks.
Between January and April 2024, I conducted the first round of pilot testing myself
reported preliminary findings in a 22-page research paper.
Through the pilot study, I identified potential methodological shortcomings
and compensated for them by adding an additional semi-spontaneous oral production task
and updating the working memory measure.
I then conducted a pilot of the new methodology in the summer of 2024, before
official starting data collection in September a year ago.
We have so far completed two rounds of data collection, and we plan to continue data
collection both in Toronto and Montreal.

Not only are the theoretical knowledge and methodological development that I have
gained from the independent project immensely valuable towards my new proposed research,
the successful execution of the project has also proven that I am capable of
conducting extensive literature reviews and designing original experimental
studies to address current research gaps.
Further, I am equally well-prepared for the practical aspects of running a study,
including participant recruitment, testing, and data analysis.

Between September 2022 and April 2025, I was a member of the Toronto Language and
Cognition (TLC) Lab headed by Professor Myrto Grigoroglou.
I worked closely with Christiana Moser, a PhD student in the lab,
on the design and data processing of her cross-linguistic study on
event conceptualization and description.
I was responsible in particular for coding multimodal speech data using ELAN.
I also participated in weekly lab meetings, where members listened and
provided feedback on each other's ongoing research projects, and took part in
other lab activities, notably participant recruitment and public outreach events.

Between April 2022 and August 2022, I worked as a research assistant and programmer
for Professor Peter Jurgec, on his project "Phonological patterns of loanwords in English".
My main responsibilities included preparing experiment stimuli and implementing the
experiment website using JavaScript and EJS.

My first research position, which I held between September 2021 and April 2022, was
working with Professor Suzi Lima to investigate
various syntactic and semantic properties of two African languages spoken in
Toronto, Tshiluba and Kirundi.
In the span of eight months, I solidified my understanding of the principles of syntactic
and semantic analysis, and I gained first-hand experience conducting linguistic field
work through planning and leading 10 elicitation sessions with language consultants.

